{"/service/ndnp/mb/batch_mb_basil_ver01/data/sn83020847/00517170835/1945122001/0713.xml":{"full_text":"MARKET ZOOMS\nAFTER WINCHELL\n\u2018TIP\u2019EVAPORATES\nStocks Turn Strong in Last\nPart of Day Peak of\nLabor Trouble Now Ex\npected in January\nWall Street Correspondence\nOf The Republican\nNew York, Dec. 18\u2014After moving\nwithin a narrow price range to 2 p.\nm., stocks today turned strong at\nthe beginning of the last hour, clos\ning at or near the day's highs with\ngains for many individual shares up\na point or more. Steels were out\nstanding in the lat^ recovery. Rails\nhad a good market the last hour\nunder the leadership of New York\nCentral. With yesterday's selling on\nthe Walter Winchell market \"tip\u201d\ndrying up. today's recovery was a\nnatural aftermath.\nA week ago today the closing aver\nage price for industrial stocks made\na new recovery high at 195.82. That\nis an increase of more than 100\npoints since the hull market started\nfrom the April (1942) wartime low of\n92.92, a third of which occurred in\nfour months, or since the war ended\nin August.\nU. S. Ready for Boom\nA week ago today, Leona id* I\u2019.\nAyres pointed out that an increase\nin unemployment, a decline in pro\nduction and a shrinkage in national\nincome meant that \u201cbusiness is now\nentering a primary postwar depres\nsion\u201d \u2014with no upturn in sight until\nnational income starts to recover,\nprobably the middle of 1946. Regard\ning the longer look ahead, the Cleve\nland economist pointed out that\n\u201cthere never has existed, anywhere,\nsuch a combination of conditions\nmaking for a boom of great intensity\nand probably of considerable dura\ntion.\u201d In advancing more than 30\npoints from the middle of August to\na week ago today, the closing aver\nage price of industrial stocks was\nanticipating the future.\nWhat Ayres said a week ago about\npresent business conditions made in\nvestors and specualtors take a more\nrealistic view of the labor situation.\nWhen the stock market began to\nadvance, from the price level of Au\ngust, reconversion to civilian produc\ntion was going surprisingly fnst.\nToday the entire automobile industry\nis marking time and a strike in the\nentire steel industry is scheduled for\nJanuary 14.\nAt the close of the market yester\nday, the industrial average, compared\nwith a week ago today, was down\n5.45 points. That for the period cov\nered is a severe decline, but it should\nnot. have been surprising when it was\nrealized that the country was head\ning for a postwar depression while\nthe average price of industrial shares\nwas advancing 30 points to the high\nest. level touched since 1930.\nAs the labor situation has thrown\na monkeywrench into reconversion,\nit is of interest to point out that\nWall street's information from Wash\nington is that the General Motors\nstrike is expected to end in the next\ncouple of weeks: that the steel strike\nis not expected to be as serious as\nanticipated: that government seizure\nof steel plants followed by an advance\nin steel wages and selling prices\nwould not be surprising: that more\nstrikes should he expected next month\nhut that January will see the peak\nof the labor troubles.\nIndustrial wages on the average\nwill be increased 15 per cent. Wall\nstreet was told by Washington today.\nIf the peak of labor troubles is wit\nnessed next month there could be a\nrapid change for the better in the\nwhole picture. Between now and\nspring the unprecedented amount of\nspending power in the hands of the\npublic will be a stock market factor.\nR. L. BARNUM.\n30 PER CENT RAISE\nREJECTED BY FORD\nUAW Leader Says Company\nDoes Not Mean End of Ne\ngotiations\u2014Truman Names\nBoard On GM Strike\nf\u00dfy the Associated Press. D.c. l\u00bb)\nThe Eord Motor Co. reiterated yes\nterday that it was unable to grant a\n30 per cent wage rate increase, while\nIn the General Motors strike Presi\ndent Truman intervened by appoint\ning a fact-finding committee.\nTn Washington, meanwhile, the\nHouse whooped through on a voice\nvote a bill by Representative Hobbs\nfD-Ala) to make the antirackeleer-\nJng act apply to labor unions. The\nmeasure now goes to the Senate,\nwhich has previously refused to pass\nsuch a measure.\nFnrtl Predicts Loss\nThe day's rapid-breaking develop\nments on the labor front. Included:\n1. The Ford Co. told the CIO\nUnited Auto Workers it would lose\nshout 335,000,600 next year, on the\nbasis of OPA price ceilings, even with\ns 18 per cent increase in production\nand no increase in wages.\nRichard T. Leonard, l\u2019AW\u2019s Ford\ndirector, told newsmen the union\nwould \"give serious consideration\u201d to\nscaling down its wage demands if the\ncompany offers an annual wage pro\nposal. He said he \"was certain\u201d the\ncompany's answer did not mean a\nbreakdown in negotiations.\n2. President Truman named a\nfact-finding hoard to inquire Into is\nsues of the 23-day-oM General Mo\ntors strike and the appointment\nbrought a prompt pledge of coopera\ntion from leaders of the striking\nUAW. Mr Truman said he also\nwould appoint \u201csoon\u201d a fact-finding\nboard to look into the steel Industry\ndispute where 70<> 000 CTO steel-work\ners have been directed to strike Janu\nary 14 for 32 a day wage increases.\nTruman Expecta Hill Sion\n3. Contrary tn the views of some\nCongressional leaders. President Tru\nman expressed confidence that Con\ngress would pssa by Christmas n\nlaw he pronosed to prohibit strikes\nuntil fact-finding boards can study\nthe Issues.\n4. The executive board of the United\npme! Workers met al Pittsburg to\ndetail nlans for the January 14 walk\nout. although CTO President Philip\nMurray said the union's wage de\nmand atlll was \u201ca negotiable pronosl-\nFart-Flndlng Board Members\nNamed to the President's fact\nfinding board were Chief Justice\nWalter P. Stacy of the North Caro\nlina supreme court, chairman: Chair\nman Lloyd K. Garrison of the War\nLabor hoard and President. Milton\nElsenhower of Kansas State college,\nbrother of Gen Dwight Eisenhower,\nTOY INBUSTRY DISPUTE ENDED\nNew York, Dec. 13\u2014(API\u2014David\nN. Abarman, attorney for the Asso\nciation of Doll Manufncturers of\nNew York. Ina., and the Stuffed Toy\nManufacturers' association, said to\nday that a wage dispute within the\ntoy Industry hart been settler! with\nthe granting of a 10-cent an-hour\nWage boost to 6600 workers.\nFINANCIAL'\nFIRST FACT-FINDING\nBOARD TROUBLED\n\u2018Guinea Pig\u2019 Oil Inquiry Hits\nSnags in Opening Hearing\n\u2014Police Crash GM Picket\nLine\nWashington, Dec. 17\u2014(AR) \u2014The\ngovernment's first experiment in use\nof fact-finding to settle a labor dis\npute nearly bogged down today on\nthe relation of profits and prices to\nlabor demands for wage increases.\nTemporarily refusing to settle the\nquestion, the \"guinea pig\u201d oil wage\nfact-finding board recessed until to\nmorrow with the announced inten\ntion of putting il\u00ab trouble before Sec\nretary of Labor Schwellenbach and\nEconomic Stabilizer John C. Collet.\nThe board's opening hearing pro\nduced considerable confusion, with\nsharp disagreement between oil in\ndustry spokesmen and representa\ntives of the Oil Workers\u2019 union. Fi\nnally the discussion became so techni\ncal that the hoard summoned labor\ndepartment legal experts for help.\nSubsequently Chairman Frank P.\nGraham told reporters the panel was\nmoving slowly because it had no\nprecedent. The oil board is regarded\nas the prototype for the panel which\nbegins hearings Wednesday in the\nGeneral Motors strike, and a fact\nfinding board yet to be appointed in\nthe steel wage dispute.\nMuch of today\u2019s session ^entered\naround demands by Lindsay P. Wal\nden, union general counsel, that the\nboard state definitely whether it\nwould relate any ultimate wage rec\nommendation to possible price in\ncreases. The union, demanding a 30\nper cent wage increase, contends the\noil industry can absorb the increase\nwithout raising prices.\nCops Charge Picket Line\nWith the aid of police squads who\ncharged through one picket line in\na flying wedge formation. General\nMotors began getting its salaried em\nployes back into its strike-bound\nMichigan plants yesterday.\nThe corporation had charged that\na strike of 175.000 CIO United Auto\nWorkers had prevented 38.000 salaried\nemployes from reporting for work\nand last week sought injunctions\nagainst pickets in Ohio, Illinois and\nNew Jersey.\nThe police charge was made against\na picket line at the GM's AC spark\nplug division in Flint. Mich., after\na police-union-rnanagement confer\nence on the picketing question.\nSome 30 workers poured through\nthe break in the picket line and\nothers followed unmolested. General\nly. nonunion employes returned to\nother GM plants without incident al\nthough at Lansing, the union charged\na plant official struck a picket.\nThe corporation, meanwhile, re\nsumed its negotiations with the\nUAW. demanding a \"corporation se\ncurity\u201d clause in any new agreement\nreached. GM requested \"appropriate\npenalties including loss of seniority\u201d\nagainst any employes participating in\nan unauthorized strike.\nSPREAD INDICATED\nIN UNEMPLOYMENT\nBecomes Less Confined to\nWar Production Centers,\nSSB Reports Bay State\nSituation Unchanged\nWashington. Dec. 15 (AP) A\ntrend indicating joblessness is spread\ning away from some former war pro\nduction areas 10 other states was re\nported today by the Social Security\nboard.\nIn a report based on unemploy\nment compensation claims, ihe board\nsaid that on a national basis the\nratio ot claims to jobs covered by in\nsurance remained virtually unchanged\nfrom last September 29 to November\n24. The ratio on the latter date was\n5.7 per cent.\n\"But behind this picture of uni\nformity In nation-wide industrial un\nemployment.\u201d the board said, \"there\nhave been marked changes in insur\nance claims loads in the various\nstates.\u201d\nThe report shows that Michigan.\nNew Jersey, Connecticut arid Illinois\n\u2014states described as having the high\nest ratio of claims to insurance-cov\nered jobs in September -had a de\ncline in claims in the November re\nport.\nMost other states experienced a\nrise in claims, the board added.\nIt said that in addition to the four\nstates with heaviest claim loads in\nSeptember, in six others fewer peo\nple were filing claims in November\nthan two months earlier. These states\nwere listed as Indiana. Ohio. Mary\nland. Pennsylvania. Wisconsin and\nNew Hampshire.\nIn California. New York. Texas and\n30 other states, more people were\nfiling claims, the board said, adding\nthat Massachusetts. North Carolina.\nKansas and Nebraska stayed virtual\nly the same over the two-month pe\nriod.\nFrom the state-by-sta te picture the\nhoard drew this conclusion: \"The fig\nures indicate the volume of unem\nployment is spreading out from the\ncenters of war industry to other\nstales. This spread represents a re\nturn tn more usual conditions of un\nemployment. with fewer peaks in\nspecific centers of industrial employ\nment.\u201d\nUNCLE SAM PLANNING\nTO SEIZE MORE BEEF\nReverts to Wartime Pro\ncedure to Get Meat for\nArmy and Navy\nWashington, Dec. 13 \u2014(AD \u2014The\ngovernment today reestablished requi\nsitioning to obtain needed supplies of\ntop grades of beef for the armed\nservices.\nSuch procedure was used during the\nwar to secure supplies for war pur\nposes. including lend-lease shipments.\nBeginning December 18. all federal\nly inspected slaughterhouses will be\nrequired to set aside, for the military\nservices. 30 per cent of their output\nof choice and good grades of steer\nand heifer beef, and 30 per cent of\ntheir grade of cow beef.\nIn announcing this action, agricul\nture department officials wild it will\ncause a slight reduction in civilian\nsupplies of the better grades of beef,\nparticularly choice steaks and roasts.\nThey said that civilians have been\nconsuming meats at. an average an\nnual rale of 185 pounds in recent\nweeks. This rate is about 15 poynds\nin excess of the amount allocated\nthem.\nThis excess civilian consumption\nwas said to reflect a diversion of a\npart of the military allocation into\ncivilian markets. Hence, the order\nrequiring more meat to be set aside,\nfor the armed forces.\nChicago. Dec. 18\u2014(AP)\u2014The eight\nstate Chicago Ordnance district can\nceled 347 contracts involving $185.-\n128,785 worth of ordnance production\nlast month, setting a new record, Col\nJohn Slezak, district chief, announced\ntoday.\nTHE SPRINGFIELD WEEKLY REPUBLICAN: SPRINGFIELD, MASS.\u2019: THURSDAY, DECEMBER 20, 1945\nNEW YORK STOCK MARKET\nSale of Stocks\nNew Yoi*k Stock exchange IJUO.MMI\nNew York Curb exchange 630,000\nBoston Stock exchange 17,385\nSales in 100's High Low Close Chf.\nA\n3 Abbott Lab Hi 82% 82 \u2014l%\n.20 Do pf U 2 112 112\n10 ACF-Brlll Mot 15% 15%\n1 Acme Stl 33% 33% 33%\u2014\n24 Adama Exp 21 20% 21 \u20194\n2 Adams-Millis 44 44 It 2\n24 Admiral Corp 18% 17% 18%+ 1%\n17 Air Reduction ....54% 53% 51%+ 1%\n8 Alaska Juneau 8% 8% 8%\n294 Alleghany Coil) 5%-\n44 Do pf 59 57% 59 +l%\n14 Do pf 74 73% 74\n9 AHor Lud Stl 38% 3814 38%\n.20 Alleg West ..105 165 105 3\n3 Alien Industries 23\u20194 23 23%\u2014\nSAI Oheni Dye 158 185 185 4\n2 Allied Kid 21% 21% 2\u2019%\n7 Allied Milla 34% 34% ,34%\n21 Allied Sirs 43\u20194 42% 43%\n1 Do pf 103\u20194 103% 103\u20194\u2014\n13 Allia-Ch Mfg 53% 52% 33 \u20194\nID Amal Leather 10% 9% 10\n1 Amerada Pet ...149 119 149 +5%\n4 Am Ag Ch Del 42% 42 42%+\n10 Am Airlines 87 XU 88%+\n14 Am Bank Note 46 37 40 2%\n1 Am Bosch 21% 21% 21%+\n3 Am Brake Shoe 49% 48% 48%\u2014\n46 Am Cable&FUd 15% 15% 15%+\n7Am Can 101 100% 101\n.20 Do pf IM 194% 198 +l\u20194\n8 Am CarAFdy 63 62% 62%\u2014\n1 Do pf 125% 125% 123%\u2014\n2 Am Ch^Cable 40 40 40\n.80 Am Chicle 136% 135% 138%+\n5 Ant Colortype 25 25 25\n11 Am Crystal Bug 25% 25 25 1\n.20 Do pf 107 107 107 1\n4 Am Distill 49% 49% 49%+ 1\n7A