4% 44%\u2014\n11 Va Caro Chem .7 8% 7\n2 Do 6 78 77% 78 +2\n3 Virginian Ry 51% 40 43 \u20142%!\n3 Do pf 41 40% 41\nw\nWabash RR pf 72% 72% 72%\n2 Waldorf Sys 1\u00bb% 1\u201c% 19%\u2014\n1 Walgreen Co 40% 4\u00ab%\u2014\n4 M's Iker (Ht GAW 97% 9\u00ab 97%+ 2\n2 Do pf 19% 19% 19%\n20 Walworth Co 13% 12% 1-I%+\n7 Ward Raking ..14 13% 14\n1.10 Do pf 10.;% 10.; 10.:\n91 Warner\u00dfrosPict 32 36% 31%+ 1%\n5 Warren Pet 19% 19% 19%-\u00ab-\n1 Wash Ga* lx 30% 30% -30\n6 Waukeeh Motor 3\u00ab 30 30\n13 Webster Tob 14% 14% 14%+\n2 Wesson O A S 35 35 35\n17 West Ind Sug 34% -3 34 1\n120 West Pen 6% pf 111 111 1D\n.50 Do pf 118% ll\u00ab% 118%\n2 W Va Pulp*Pap 37% 36% 36% 1\n3 Western Air L 38% 37 38%-r 1\n16 West Maryland 11% 11 11%+\n1 Do pf 2 29% 29% 2\u00bb%-\n1 West Pac 50 50 50\nII West Un Tel A 52% 51 52%+\n17 Westing Air Br 35% 35 .35%+\n46 Westing Elec 36 35 36\n1 Weston El Inst 43 43 43\n1 Wheeling Steel 44% 44% 44%\n.So Dn pr pf 100% l\u2019*o 10**%\n2 White Dent 29 29 29 1\n8 White Motor 39% .39% 38%-*\n4 White Seu Mach 15% 15% 15%+\n2 Wilcox Oil 10% 10% in%-\n31 Willvs Overland 22% 21% 22\n35 Wi%on A Co 18% 18 18\n5 Do pf I\u00bbm>% ]no% ion%+\n2 Wilson Jnne\u00ab 21% 21% 21%\u2014\n3 Woodward Iron 35% 3<% .34% 1%\n13 Wool worth F W 48% '49% 49%\n3 M nithing FAM 62% 62 62 U\n6 Wyand Wor 21% 21% 21%+\nY\n5 Yale Towne .22% 21% 22%\n2 Young Sug A W 27% 27% 27%\u2014\n8 Youngat SAT 6ft% 65% 66% I\n8 Youngat Stl Dr 2.5 24% 25\n7.\n7 Zenith Radin 40% 39% 40\n24 Zonite Products 11 10% 11\nADMIRAL H. K. HEWITT\nFIGHTS MERGER PLAN\nSenators Hear Him Back\nNavy Proposal for a Na\ntional Security Council\nWashington. Dec. 15 (A Pi\nSenators heard Admiral H. K. Hewitt\nargue today against a single depart\nment of defense and putting the navy\nunder the control of \u201cthose w r hp do\nnot understand its functions and\nproblems.\u201d\nThe member of the navy general\nboard told the Senate military com\nmittee there would be immediate\nI \"chaos\u201d in the navy if the armed serv\nice* were combined.\nThe army wants a single defense\nse.up under one cabinet member.\nHewitt backed a navy plan to retain\n1 separate war and navy departments,\nwith a national security council co\nordinating their operations. On the\ncouncil would be the secretaries of\nata war and navy, the chairman of\na national security resources board,\nheads of emergency agencies and the\nI secretary of air\u2014if a separate air de\npartment Is established\nStrategic plans and their execution\nwould be left to the joint chiefs of\nstaff.\nHewitt said he thought It would be\nbetter to have several peop\u2019e. rather\nthan one secretary of defense, de\n1 ermine what jmrt of the defense\n1 budget should go to each service.\nFINANCIAL'\nU.S. COURT FINES\nCHEMICAL FIRMS\nFour Leading Companies and\nFour Officials Fined $52,-\n500 for Violation of Sher\nman Anti-Trust Law\nTrenton. N. J., Dec. 15 \u2014(AP)\nFederal Judgre Phillip Forman im\npowed fines here loday totalling $52.-\n500 on four of the nation\u2019s largest\nlaboratory chemicals manufacturers\nand four company officials under in\ndictment by a federal g>-and jury on\ncharges nf violating the Sherman\nanti-trust act.\nAll of the defendants, v* ho were in\ndicted by a federal grand jury here\nin November. 1943. and pleaded in\nnocent, changed their plea to no\ncontent before the court sessions got\nunderway today.\nThe four firms, ordered to pay the\nmaximum fine of SSOOO apiece on\neach of the two counts of the in\ndictment charging conspiracy to fix\nprices, suppress competition and to\nmonopolize the sale of laboratory\nchemicals w%re:\nMerck Co., of Rahway; J. T.\nRaker Chemical Co., of Phillipsburg;\nGeneral Chemical Co., of New York\ncity: and Mallinckrodt Chemical\nWorks of St Louis, Mo.\nIndividuals fined were:\nJames J. Kerrigan of Summit, vice\npresident of Merck Co.. $2500 on\neach count.\nHerbert H. Garis of Eastnn. Pa.,\npresident of J. T. Baker Co.. $2500 on\neach count.\nArnold D. Alt of St Louis, chief of\nthe laboratory chemical division of\nMallinckrodt Works. SSOO on each\ncount.\nLeonard F. Eiklor of New York\ncity, director of the fine chemicals\ndepartment of General Che lical Co.,\n$750 on each count.\nOn the recommendation of Samuel\nFla tow. special assistant to U. S. At\ntorney-General Tom Clark, who ap\npeared for the government. Judge\nForman ordered dismissal of charges\nagainst three other Indi visuals who\nwere named in the indictment but\nwere not on trial.\nThey were: Joseph K. L. Snyder\nof Rahway, general sales director nf\nMerck Co.: John W. Wilson of\nRahway, Merck\u2019s chief price control\ndepartment head: and Ralph A. Clark\nof Easton, vice-president of the J. T\nBaker Co.\nSENATE APPROVES\nWATER PROJECTS\nWestern Massachusetts and\nConnecticut Valley Flood\nControl Works Included in\nAppropriation\nWashington, Dec. 15 (AP) A;\n$124,775,000 appropriation for naviga-!\ntion and flood control won Senate!\napproval today.\nThe sum. requested by President\nTruman and the army engineers to*\nput water projects back on a peace-;\ntime basis, is contained in a deficiency\nsupply bill already passed by the 1\nHouse.\nThe Senate added two projects\nemitted by the House\u2014s3,ooo,ooo for\nthe Conemaugh river reservoir. Pa.,\nand $1,000,000 for the Hulah reservoir,\nOkL A $1,500,000 appropriation for the\ni Mansfield Hollow reservoir, Ct., was\nstricken from the bilk\nHouse concurrence in the Senate\nchanges would send the measure to\n\u25a0the White House, climaxing a heated\n[dispute over whether flood control!\nand navigation should be covered in 1\na deficiency bill.\nThe House appropriations commit-;\ntee had refused to approve a cent fori\nthe projects on the ground that they*\nshould be handled in the regular war!\ndepartment appropriation bill next!\nJuly.\nOverriding the committee. the;\nHouse backed up the President s con- 1\ntention that war-halted rivers and!\nHood projects should be resumed,\npromptly.\nSome of the larger reservoirs em\nbrace hydroelectric development as]\nwell as Hood control.\nAmong the projects and the sums\nappropriated for each are:\nRivers and harbors: Connecticut I\nriver below Hartford. $75,000.\nFlood control (general): Knights\n-1 ville reservoir. Mass.. $14,006: Hart\nford, Ct.. $285 000; Winsted. CL. $132.-\npOO; Springfield. Mass. (Mill river).\n$12,000: West Springfield, Mass. (Ag\n[awam river). $338,000: Riverdale.\nMass.. $403,600: Chicopee. Mass.. $170,-\n!000; Holyoke. Mass.. $500,000.\nSENATE OK\u2019S RAISE\nIN CIVIL SERVICE PAY\nIncrease Averages 11 Per\nCent for About Third of\nU. S. Workers Said Not\nEnough of Boost\nWashington. Dec. 18 (AP) A\nsliding-scale pay increase averaging\n11 per cent for an estimated 1.100,000\ngovernment workers was approved in\nthe Senate today and sent to the\nHouse.\nSenator Byrd (D-Va). who backed\nthe measure as a substitute for a\nmore liberal one by Senator Downey\n(D-CaD. said it would offset the in-\ncreased cost of living for all workers i\nnow under classified civil service. He I\nsaid, however, that it covered only\nabout one-third of the 3.000.000-odd\ngovernment workers.\nDowney, who tried in vain for two\nweeks to win a fiat 20 per cent hike.\nbitterly protested the Byrd substi\ntute.\nI \u201dIf this was offered by any large\ncorporation or business to its em\nployes. the workers would go off the\njob the following day.\u201d Downey told\nthe Senate.\nRut the Senate on a 4\u00ab-to-19 roll\ncall vote accepted the plan sponsored\njointly by Senators Rvrd. Hickenloop\ner iR-Ia) and Hart (R-Ct).,\nByrd offet*ed a table which showed\nthat government workers formerly\ngetting |1440 annually would receive\n$1832 or an Increase of 13.33 percent.\nThe rate of the pay boost decreases\na* salaries mount until workers get\nting SBSOO would receive $9067. or an\nincrease of 6.68 per cent.\nCertificate Rate Increase\nUrged by Aubrex Lanston\nNew York. Dec. 13\u2014(AP) \u2014An In\ncrease from per cent to 1 per cent\nin the treasury certificate coupon\n\u2022\u2022ate was urged today by Aubrey G,\nLanston. vice-president of First Bos\nton Corp., as a means of stabilizing\ninterest rates at prevailing levels.\n1n a statement l\u00abanston said that\nunless the government takes positive\nsteps toward such stabllhntlon. there\nwill ensue a progression in monetary\nand hanking conditions toward in\nfiation and ultimate losses to sav\nings bank depositors and more than\n170,000.000 insurance policy holders.\nMARKET SLUMP\nIS BLAMED ON\nWINCHELL\u2018NEWS\u2019\nRadio Prediction of \u2018Severe\nBreak\u2019 Makes Trouble\nMarket Was Due for Some\nSort of Mishap\nWall Street I orn^pondance\nOf Th. Rrpahllcan\nNpw York, Dee. 17 Today's stock\nmarket did not stand up well consid\nering rhe character of news that put\nit down in the early trading. Indus\ntrial and rail averages after II o'clock\nragged hourly, closing down 3.39 and\n1.37 respectively.\nWalter Winchell waa credited by\nWall street for the hrealc in the mar\nket the first hour this morning on\nj heavy trading that carried a long\nI list of shares down from one to three\ni points or mor\u00ab with Eastern Air\nnosediving o. I\u20193 from Satur\nday's closing of 128, with the average\nI for 30 representative industrial shares\ndown 2.02 and for 20 rails off 1.85.\nIn his radio broadcast last night.\nWinchell said that a severe break was\ndust ahead in the stock market, and\nthat his information had come from\ninsiders.\u201d Winchell's opinions on any\nsubject do not rate high in the fl-\nI naneial district, but Wall street real\nizes that his nation-wide audience on\nSunday nights includes many ines\nperienced stock speculators who might\nwell be influenced by what a well\nknown radio columnist had to say.\nWall street knows that the old days\nof \"insiders\u201d are done with, and rea\nsons that even if there were any\nI now Winchell would be one of the\nlast persons in whom they confided.\nOnly last week it was reported in\ni this column that the stock exchange\nis making it plain that the exehang#\nis keeping a close eye on employes of\nmember firms to see that they live\n:up to the rules governing their re\nlations with customers: that It tnld\nmembers that the exchange does not\nlike the reappearance in a booming\nstock market of the mysterious\ni they\u201d: that a customers man of one\nI firm had been suspended for hie\nhabit of inducing customers to buy\nor sell because \u201dthey\u201d are putting a\nstock up or down.\nWhat people all over the financial\ni district today were asking was \"Will\nI Winchell he made to tell by either the\nI stock exchange or the Securities and\nI Exchange commission who were the\ninsiders\u2019 that told him the stock\nmarket was going to break?\"\nRut what Winchell said over the\nradio is not the real explanation for\nwhat happened in the stock market\nI during the first hour this morning.\nI Since the bull marker started in April\n1342. the president of the exchange\nl repeatedly has warned the public,\nmany of whom doubtless listened to\nWinchell last night, against speculat\ning in a stock simply because rhe\nI price was cheap. Because this warn\ni ing was ignored, the market was\ni ready for a break.\nTalk of more inflation- is in the air.\nj The public, with moi^ money than\never before, has beei^ buying stocks'\nas a hedge against inflation. Recently\nthe stock market, increasingly, has\nI been thin on both the up and down\nside. Not much buying or selling was\nnecessary to bring about wide price\nfluctuations in individual stocks.\ni Some stocks came down during the\nfirst hour this morning the way they\nhave been going up. Take Eastern\nAir Line for example. That stock re\ncently sold at 134 against the low\nfor the year of 39 The dividend is\n81. A stock selling at 134 receiving\nan annual dividend of >1 offers an in\ni come return of less than 1 per cent\nSpeculators have been buying East\nern Air Line for its growth outlook\nas well as for a hedge against infla\ntion.\nOne thing can be said with cer\ntainty about what happened in the\nmarket today in the early trading. It\nstrengthened the technical position\nof the market. R. L. BARNUM.\nBUILDINGINDmY\nIRKED BY U.S. PLAN\n\u2018Lnworkable and Unrealistic\u2019\nIs Verdict After Housing\nConference OPA At-\ntitude Condemned\nWashington. Dec. IS\u2014(AP)\u2014Con\nstruction industry leaders today as\nsailed the government s new bousing\nprogram as \u201cunworkable\u201d and \u201cun\nrealistic.\u201d They made these asser\ntions after adjournment of a two\nday government-sponsored housin<\n1 conference and following statements\ni by federal officials that the session\nhad accomplished its purpose.\nH. R. Northup, secretary-manager\nof the National Retail Lumber Deal\ners\u2019 association, told a news confer\nmce that management delegates\n\u201cdidn\u2019t com#* here to get shoved\naround for two days.**\nWe would like the idea of a con\nference Northup added, \u201cif the gov\nernment people had not made up\nTheir minds before it was called on\njust what was going to be done.\u201d\nDouglas Whitlock, former president\nof th# l Producers Council, inc.. said\nhe had understood the conference was\nbe '^operative tndustry-labor\ng\", !*'\u25a0\".iking \u201cThe 00-\nj operation.\u201d Whitlock said, \u201cam unted\nto this. Wp were told: \u2018Here\u2019s a pri\n-1 oritv -ogram and you are going to\ntake ft.*\nRoth Northup and Whitlock con\ntended that the primary construction\nbottleneck is OPA s \"unrealistic price\npolicy.**\nWhile he pledged industry coopera\ntion Whitlock said in effect that since\nthe government had initiated the pro\ngram. it would have to take responsi\nbility for the outcome.\nThe program provides for earmark\ning 50 per cent of all building supplies\nfor homes costing SIO,OOO or less. It\nalso Includes administration indorse\nment of legislation to fix price ceil\nings on new and existing houses.\nUNRRA. HOUSING HINDS\nVOTED BY COMMITTEE\nWashington. Dec. 13\u2014(AP)\u2014The\nSenate appropriations committee tn\nnight added $100,000,000 for UNRRA\nand sl7l 127.00*) for veterans* hous\ning to the $1,500,000,000 deficiency hill\nrecently passed by the House.\nThe UNRRA fund would b\u00bb\u2018 an ini\ntial instalment on the $1,350,000,000\nwhich the United States is slated to\nontribute for the organization's next\n115 \u00bbi year The House has passed\na bin authorizing the contribution\nand the Senate foreign relations com\nmittee today approved it.\nM iSS. COMPAXVS I\u2019l iN OK\u2019D\nPhiladelphia. Dec. 13 (AP) The\nSecurities and Exchange commission\napproved today a plan under which\nCentral Power and Light Co (Mass.)\nwould sell electric, water and ice\nproperties located In Texas to Cen\ntral Power and Light Co.. Texas, and\nthen dissolve. Transactions in con\nnection with the plan include the\n:sbue h? the Texas company to the\nMassachusetts company of 100.000\n\u2022Mraa o f too par value preferred\nend 202.170 shares of no par value\nI cummou.\n13","height":"25978","width":"19483"}}
